## Layout

```
.                  # Hono Worker (Better Auth on D1)
  src/index.ts              Hono app: /api/auth/* (better-auth), /api/me, /api/chat (AI), /api/usage
  src/lib/better-auth/      auth() factory — drizzleAdapter(drizzle(env.DB), 'sqlite');
                            stripe.ts — @better-auth/stripe plugin (Pro plan + metered overage)
  src/lib/billing/          constants.ts (plan knobs) + usage.ts (D1 gate + Stripe meter events)
  src/lib/email/            sendPasswordResetEmail() — Cloudflare Email Sending binding
  src/db/schema.ts          GENERATED by @better-auth/cli — do not edit by hand
  src/db/app-schema.ts      Hand-written app tables (ai_usage) — survives auth:generate
  drizzle/                  SQL migrations generated by drizzle-kit from schema.ts + app-schema.ts
  scripts/stripe-bootstrap.ts  Idempotent Stripe meter/product/price/webhook provisioning
  wrangler.jsonc            D1 `DB`, `AI`, `EMAIL` (send_email), assets `ASSETS` → ./web/dist,
                            STRIPE_*_PRICE_ID vars
  better-auth.config.ts     Schema-generation config (uses better-sqlite3 :memory:)
  drizzle.config.ts         dialect: sqlite, driver: d1-http, schema: [schema.ts, app-schema.ts]

web/               # Vite React SPA (shadcn preset buFznsW, radix-lyra, phosphor icons)
  src/App.tsx               Auth-gated root (loading → dashboard or login card)
  src/components/login-card.tsx, dashboard.tsx
  src/pages/chat.tsx        Streaming AI chat (useChat → /api/chat) on shadcn message-scroller,
                            behind RequireAuth; free-tier meter + 402 upgrade CTA
  src/pages/billing.tsx     Plan/usage card, Stripe Checkout upgrade, portal, cancel/restore
  src/pages/forgot-password.tsx, reset-password.tsx   Password-reset flow
  src/lib/auth-client.ts    Thin fetch wrapper hitting /api/auth/* and /api/usage
```

Worker serves the SPA through the `assets` binding with `not_found_handling: single-page-application`. `run_worker_first: ["/api/*"]` gates the Worker in front of the assets handler for API routes.

## Design system

This project was generated with the **{{ design_system }}** design system. The look lives entirely in a token layer: `web/src/index.css` imports `web/src/styles/{{ design_system }}.css` (palette, fonts, radius, motion as CSS custom properties + a shadcn `@theme` mapping). Components consume semantic tokens (`--bg-0`, `--fg-1`, `--accent`, `--font-display`, …), so the design system swaps without touching component code. All three (`nothing`, `apex`, `onyx`) ship under `web/src/styles/` and are dual-mode — every color is `light-dark(…)`, defaulting to the OS with a System/Light/Dark toggle (`web/src/components/theme-toggle.tsx`, applied as `data-theme` on `<html>`; a pre-paint script in `index.html` avoids FOUC). To switch later: change the import in `index.css` and add that system's fonts to `web/package.json` (see the `@import` lines at the top of each token file).

## Marketing page

**All landing-page copy lives in `web/src/content/marketing.ts` — edit that file first to make the page yours.** Every section reads from the typed `MarketingContent` object, and sections hide themselves when their slice is empty (an empty `testimonials` array renders nothing — never ship fake social proof). The page order is a conversion funnel: value prop → proof → benefits → how it works → numbers → social proof → pricing → FAQ → final CTA. CRO rules baked into the defaults: the hero headline is a value proposition (not the brand name — that lives in the nav), one accent CTA repeated (hero → pricing → final band), a risk-reversal line beside every CTA, and the pricing section mirrors the built-in Stripe billing (`src/lib/billing/constants.ts` + `scripts/stripe-bootstrap.ts` — keep them in sync if you change the plan shape). The hero `proof` field switches the proof artifact: `{ mode: "image", src, alt, caption? }` renders a product screenshot in a hard-edged instrument frame (drop the file in `web/public`), `{ mode: "none" }` hides the slot.

**The page speaks to end users, never about the implementation.** Default copy describes the generated product (an AI assistant with accounts and usage billing) in user vocabulary — no stack names, no repo links, no deploy commands. That information lives here and in the README. Footer links (`marketing.footer.links`) are placeholder PRIVACY/TERMS/CONTACT anchors to wire per project; the theme toggle lives in the footer (in-app pages keep their own).

`/` (`web/src/pages/landing.tsx`) composes Nav → Hero → Ticker → FeatureRow → HowItWorks → StatsBand → SocialProof → PricingSection → FaqSection → CtaBand → Footer from `web/src/components/marketing/`. Two kinds of flourish sit on top of the token layer, both design-system-agnostic:

- **WebGL shaders** (`@paper-design/shaders-react`): the hero's dithered sphere (`hero-backdrop.tsx`) and the closing band's grain gradient (`cta-band.tsx`). Shader colors are resolved at runtime from CSS custom properties via `use-token-colors.ts` (paints tokens onto a probe element and reads back the computed color), so they follow the active design system *and* the live theme toggle. Animation speed drops to 0 under `prefers-reduced-motion`.
- **Motion primitives** (`web/src/components/motion/`, adapted from [react-bits](https://reactbits.dev), built on `motion`): `SplitText` (staggered hero headline), `DecryptedText` (scramble-in mono metadata), `CountUp` (stats tick up in view), `Reveal` (scroll-in fade/rise). All render statically under `prefers-reduced-motion` and keep real text available to screen readers (`sr-only` + `aria-hidden` pattern).

`SpotlightCard` (mouse-tracked `--accent-subtle` glow) and `Ticker` (pure-CSS marquee) round out the set. Everything uses semantic tokens only — swapping the design system restyles the whole page, shaders included.

## AI chat

`POST /api/chat` is a streaming chatbot built on the `AI` binding (Workers AI), routed through the **`default` AI Gateway** for caching/observability. It uses the Vercel AI SDK: `streamText` + `workers-ai-provider`'s `createWorkersAI({ binding, gateway: { id: "default" } })` server-side (model `@cf/meta/llama-4-scout-17b-16e-instruct`), and `useChat` from `@ai-sdk/react` in `web/src/pages/chat.tsx`.

- **Auth-gated.** The route 401s without a session — anonymous traffic must never reach `env.AI.run` and burn neurons. The UI lives behind `RequireAuth` at `/chat`.
- **Metered.** Before touching `env.AI` the route checks the caller's billing state and 402s (`code: "free_quota_exhausted"`) when a free-tier user has burned their monthly allotment. After each stream, `streamText`'s `onFinish` reports `usage.totalTokens` via `ctx.waitUntil` — a D1 upsert for everyone plus a Stripe meter event for subscribers. See "Billing (Stripe)" below.
- **Transcript is stateless.** No chat-history table: `useChat` holds the transcript in React state and re-sends the full message array each turn for multi-turn context (only token *usage* is persisted, in `ai_usage`). To persist transcripts, add a table in `src/db/app-schema.ts` and key it on `session.user.id`.
- **Local dev bills real usage.** `wrangler dev` (so `mise dev`) proxies AI to Cloudflare's GPU network — no `--remote` needed, but inference is charged even locally. Pick a smaller model or mock during heavy iteration.
- Swap the model by editing the `workersai("…")` id in `src/index.ts`. The `default` gateway is auto-provisioned on first use; create a named gateway in the dashboard if you want custom caching/rate-limit rules.

## Billing (Stripe)

Subscriptions with usage-based overage for AI chat tokens, built on the official `@better-auth/stripe` plugin plus Stripe Billing Meters. One "Pro" plan: **$20/month, 1,000,000 tokens included, then $5 per additional 1M tokens**. Signed-in users without a subscription get a **free 50k tokens per UTC calendar month**. All knobs live in `src/lib/billing/constants.ts` and `scripts/stripe-bootstrap.ts` — keep them in sync if you change the plan shape.

**Who counts what** (the load-bearing split):

- **D1 (`ai_usage`)** gates the free tier and feeds the UI meter for everyone. Buckets are UTC calendar months keyed `(user_id, period)` — a new month simply starts a new row, no cron. A request that starts under the cap streams to completion; the *next* request 402s.
- **Stripe's meter** is the billing source of truth for subscribers. Every subscriber request reports `usage.totalTokens` as a meter event (`event_name: "ai_tokens"`); the metered price's graduated tiers make the first 1M free and price the rest — the Worker never computes "past the allotment?". The D1 calendar month won't exactly align with a subscriber's Stripe billing period; that's cosmetic (UI meter only), the money math happens entirely in Stripe.
- Meter events are fire-and-forget (`ctx.waitUntil`); a failure under-bills, never over-bills, and never breaks chat.

**Plumbing:**

- `src/lib/better-auth/stripe.ts` builds the plugin: `createCustomerOnSignUp`, the `pro` plan (`STRIPE_PRO_PRICE_ID`), and the metered overage price as an extra checkout line item (`lineItems: [{ price: STRIPE_METERED_PRICE_ID }]` — metered line items must NOT carry a `quantity`, Stripe rejects it).
- **Graceful degradation:** the plugin is only mounted when `env.STRIPE_SECRET_KEY` is set (see `auth()` in `src/lib/better-auth/index.ts`). A fresh project signs up and chats on the free tier with zero Stripe config; billing endpoints 404 until configured (the `/billing` page surfaces the setup hint).
- Plugin endpoints ride under `/api/auth`: `subscription/upgrade` (Checkout), `subscription/list`, `subscription/cancel` (portal confirm flow), `subscription/restore`, `subscription/billing-portal`, and the webhook at **`/api/auth/stripe/webhook`** (handles `checkout.session.completed` + `customer.subscription.*`, syncing the `subscription` table).
- `GET /api/usage` (session-gated, D1-only) returns `{ plan, tokensUsed, allotment, period, subscription }` for the chat header meter and `/billing`.

**Setup:**

```bash
# 1. Put a Stripe secret key in .dev.vars (sandbox) or the environment
# 2. Create meter + product + prices, patch price IDs into wrangler.jsonc:
mise run stripe:bootstrap
# 3. Local webhooks:
stripe listen --forward-to localhost:8787/api/auth/stripe/webhook   # → whsec_… into .dev.vars
# 4. Deployed Worker:
mise run stripe:secrets                                  # uploads both secrets from .dev.vars
mise run stripe:bootstrap -- --url https://your-app.example   # creates the webhook endpoint
```

The bootstrap is idempotent — objects are found by lookup key (`pro-base`, `pro-metered-tokens`) and meter event name, so re-running is safe. Env surface: secrets `STRIPE_SECRET_KEY` + `STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET` (wrangler secrets / `.dev.vars`), vars `STRIPE_PRO_PRICE_ID` + `STRIPE_METERED_PRICE_ID` (in `wrangler.jsonc`, mirrored under `env.preview.vars`).

**Schema ownership (important):** `user.stripeCustomerId` and the `subscription` table are emitted by `@better-auth/cli` (the stripe plugin is registered in `better-auth.config.ts` with a placeholder client purely for schema generation) — they survive `mise run auth:generate`. The `ai_usage` table is hand-written in **`src/db/app-schema.ts`**, which the CLI never touches; `drizzle.config.ts` merges both files. Never hand-edit `src/db/schema.ts` — regeneration eats it.

## Password reset (email)

The forgot-password flow is wired end to end on Better Auth's built-in endpoints — **no schema change** (reset tokens live in the existing `verification` table).

- **UI.** A "Forgot password?" link on the sign-in form → `/forgot-password` (request a reset by email) → Better Auth emails a link → `/reset-password` (reads `?token=`/`?error=` off the URL and sets a new password). Both pages sit behind `RequireGuest` like login/signup.
- **Server seam.** `src/lib/better-auth/index.ts` sets `emailAndPassword.sendResetPassword` in the env-scoped `auth()` factory (not in static `options.ts` — it needs `env` for the EMAIL binding). Without that callback Better Auth refuses `/request-password-reset`. The client calls live in `web/src/lib/auth-client.ts` (`requestPasswordReset`, `resetPassword`).
- **Delivery.** `src/lib/email/reset-password.ts` sends via the Cloudflare Email Sending binding (`send_email`, named `EMAIL` in wrangler.jsonc) — no third-party API keys. **You must onboard the sending domain once** before reset emails deliver: dashboard *Compute → Email Service → Email Sending → Onboard Domain*, or `wrangler email sending enable <domain>`. Then point `EMAIL_FROM` in `wrangler.jsonc` `vars` at an address on that domain (default placeholder: `noreply@example.com`). Until onboarded, sends fail with `E_SENDER_NOT_VERIFIED`; the `/request-password-reset` endpoint still returns 200 (anti-enumeration), so the UI doesn't leak the misconfig.
- **Not a fan-out surface.** `send_email` isn't one of the tripwire-watched bindings (queues/services/DOs/crons/workflows/tail) — email can't recurse into this Worker — so no `REVIEWED` entry is needed.

## Commands (mise tasks)

All project commands run through mise — see `mise.toml` for the full list, or `mise tasks`.

First-run checklist (copier's `_tasks` already ran `mise trust`, `mise install`, and the JS installs on render):

```bash
bunx wrangler login       # one-time CF auth (skip if you're going headless)
mise init                 # seeds .dev.vars, applies local migrations, and — if
                          # wrangler is authenticated — provisions the remote D1
                          # (patching wrangler.jsonc), BETTER_AUTH_SECRET, and
                          # remote migrations
mise dev                  # http://localhost:8787
mise deploy               # ship to *.workers.dev
```

Common loops:

```bash
mise run dev              # builds SPA (source-tracked) then wrangler dev
mise run typecheck        # Worker + web together
mise run web:build        # SPA only; mise caches based on sources
mise run deploy           # web:build -> wrangler deploy
mise run update-from-template  # `copier update` against the parent template
```

For a fresh worktree (e.g. fulcrum task branch) where you want production-like data without touching remote resources:

```bash
mise trust                # one-time per worktree path — mise refuses to load
                          # mise.toml from an untrusted path (the parent
                          # repo's trust doesn't transfer to a new worktree)
mise run worktree-init    # deps + .dev.vars + wipe & re-migrate local D1 +
                          # pull prod data via read-only `wrangler d1 export --remote`
```

The export goes through D1's R2-staged export endpoint and is applied locally via the `sqlite3` CLI (bypasses wrangler's ~1MB per-statement limit on local execute). The script strips `d1_migrations` and `sqlite_sequence` rows from the export before applying — those are wrangler's internal bookkeeping that `migrate:local` has already populated, so re-importing them would collide on PRIMARY KEY. If the project adds FTS or other virtual tables, narrow `wrangler d1 export` with `--table=<name>` flags so local triggers — not exported shadow-table INSERTs — populate the index.

## Schema & migration flow

Better Auth's schema is **generated, not hand-written** — but the project has two schema files: `src/db/schema.ts` (CLI-generated: auth tables + stripe plugin's `subscription` / `user.stripeCustomerId`) and `src/db/app-schema.ts` (hand-written app tables like `ai_usage`; the CLI never touches it). `drizzle.config.ts` reads both. Put custom tables in `app-schema.ts`, never in `schema.ts`. When adding a better-auth plugin or changing `src/lib/better-auth/options.ts`:

```bash
mise run auth:generate    # regenerates src/db/schema.ts from better-auth.config.ts
mise run db:generate      # drizzle-kit turns schema.ts into drizzle/NNNN_*.sql
mise run migrate:local    # wrangler d1 migrations apply --local
```

Remote D1 migrations apply automatically on push to `main` when Workers Builds is connected (see the Deploy section) — `bun run ci:build` runs `db:migrate:remote` before `wrangler deploy`. `mise run migrate:remote` / `bun run db:migrate:remote` remain available as an escape hatch for out-of-band fixes or local `mise deploy`.

Ordering inside `ci:build`: install deps → build SPA → apply D1 migrations → (Workers Builds then runs `wrangler deploy`). D1 lands before the Worker, so migrations must stay forward-compatible with the currently-deployed Worker — destructive schema changes require two pushes (first push: code tolerating both schemas; second push: the drop).

Non-production branches run `ci:build:preview` and upload a *version* of the standalone `{{ worker_name }}-preview` Worker via `wrangler versions upload --env preview`. `mise run builds:connect` wires that trigger on `{{ worker_name }}-preview` (not on `{{ worker_name }}`) precisely so the `--env preview` block in `wrangler.jsonc` takes effect — Workers Builds connections are per-Worker, so a trigger on `{{ worker_name }}-preview` is the only way to land a PR-branch deploy on the preview Worker with its preview-DB binding.

> **Forward-compat rule still applies — but to the preview DB.** Every non-main branch shares `{{ d1_database_name }}-preview`, so the first preview deploy of any branch applies its migrations to that shared DB. If two branches' migrations conflict, drop `d1_migrations` on `{{ d1_database_name }}-preview` and re-run `mise run migrate:remote-preview`. Destructive drops still need the two-pushes pattern (tolerant Worker first, drop second), against either D1.

The preview Worker (`{{ worker_name }}-preview`) has to exist before `mise run builds:connect` can wire its trigger. Bootstrap with `mise run d1:create-preview && mise run deploy:preview && mise run secret:put-preview`, then re-run `mise run builds:connect`. The task is idempotent and skips the preview trigger gracefully if the Worker isn't there yet.

`better-auth.config.ts` uses an in-memory `better-sqlite3` DB because the CLI doesn't need a real connection to emit drizzle table definitions — only the adapter shape.

## Tests

`mise run test` (or `bun run test`) — vitest runs everything inside real `workerd` via `@cloudflare/vitest-pool-workers`. D1 migrations from `./drizzle` apply to an in-memory test DB; the prod `wrangler.jsonc` config (sans the production `database_id`, which workerd ignores) supplies bindings; `BETTER_AUTH_SECRET`, `BETTER_AUTH_URL`, and dummy Stripe values are injected via miniflare bindings in `vitest.config.ts`. Use `mise run test:watch` while iterating.

**Outbound network is stubbed in tests.** Because the dummy `STRIPE_SECRET_KEY` activates the stripe plugin, every sign-up fires `createCustomerOnSignUp`. `test/stripe-mock.ts` (installed by `test/setup.ts`) patches `globalThis.fetch` — tests and the Worker share one workerd isolate, so this intercepts the Worker's outbound Stripe calls — answers the customer search/list/create flows, and **throws on any other outbound fetch**. If a new feature legitimately fetches externally, add a handler there.

What's covered today:

- **`test/auth.test.ts`** — sign-up → /api/me → sign-in → sign-out, end-to-end through `SELF.fetch()`. Locks in the four auth gotchas below — any regression flips the suite red.
- **`test/chat.test.ts`** — `/api/chat` rejects anonymous requests (401) and empty payloads (400). These guards run before `env.AI.run`, so they're testable without a GPU; the streaming path itself can't run under vitest-pool-workers (no GPU, the AI binding proxies to remote) — verify it manually via `mise dev`.
- **`test/billing.test.ts`** — `/api/usage` gating and shapes, the 402 free-quota gate on `/api/chat` (runs before `env.AI`, so GPU-free), pro un-gating via a seeded `subscription` row, the stripe webhook route (mounted + signature verification works under workerd), and the Checkout session body (metered line item present, without `quantity`).
- **`test/lib/billing-quota.test.ts`** — `currentPeriod()` UTC boundaries, free-cap edge cases, and the fresh-render safety: `auth()` mounts no stripe plugin when `STRIPE_SECRET_KEY` is unset.
- **`test/password-reset.test.ts`** — full forgot-password path through `SELF.fetch()`: sign-up → request-password-reset → reset-password → sign-in with the new password (old password + bad tokens rejected), plus the anti-enumeration 200. The reset token is read from the `verification` table; miniflare's local `send_email` stub captures the email so the send path runs without a live mail service.
- **`test/lib/derive-trusted-origins.test.ts`** — workers.dev auto-derive, custom domain, malformed URL, CSV merge.
- **`test/safeguards/no-runaway-fanout.test.ts`** — the **fan-out tripwire**.

The tripwire is the headline. A worker that calls itself in a loop (or a queue consumer that re-publishes to its own queue, or a DO alarm scheduling more alarms) can't be reached by Cloudflare's public-facing kill-switch — DNS/routes/custom domains stay external. The protection has to live inside the worker. See [pizzaconsole.com/blog/posts/programming/cf-overage](https://pizzaconsole.com/blog/posts/programming/cf-overage) for the threat model.

This template intentionally **does not** prescribe one safeguard pattern (hop-count headers, queue envelopes, alarm budgets, …) because different fan-out shapes need different mitigations. Instead, the tripwire fails the build the moment any of these surfaces appears in `wrangler.jsonc` without an explicit acknowledgment:

- `queues.producers`, `queues.consumers`
- `services` (service bindings)
- `durable_objects.bindings`
- `triggers.crons`
- `workflows`
- `tail_consumers`

When the tripwire fires after you add a binding:

1. Decide what stops a runaway loop for that surface — a hop-count header on outgoing fetches, a `depth` field on queue messages with a low `max_retries` + DLQ, a per-DO alarm budget in storage, a shared-secret + counter on a service binding caller, etc.
2. Uncomment / add the corresponding entry in the `REVIEWED` map at the top of `test/safeguards/no-runaway-fanout.test.ts` with a one-line note pointing at the test that proves the safeguard.
3. Add a behavioral test under `test/safeguards/` that exercises the surface end-to-end and asserts it terminates (e.g. a queue consumer test that tries to re-publish, sees the depth guard fire, and stops).

Removing a binding? Delete its `REVIEWED` entry in the same change.

`bun run ci:build` runs `bun run test` before `wrangler deploy`, so a failing suite blocks production deploys (and previews via `ci:build:preview`). `mise run ci:local` is the local mirror.

SPA component tests aren't here yet — the auth e2e flow already exercises the same `/api/auth/*` endpoints `web/src/lib/auth-client.ts` calls. Add `vitest` + `@testing-library/react` under `web/` when there's UI logic worth covering directly.

## Deploy

Two paths. **Local ad-hoc:**

```bash
mise deploy
```

**Push to deploy (recommended once the project is on GitHub):**

```bash
mise run builds:connect
```

Idempotently calls the Cloudflare API to attach this repo to `{{ worker_name }}` and create two triggers:

- `main` → `bun run ci:build` → `wrangler deploy` (production, on `{{ worker_name }}`)
- all other branches → `bun run ci:build:preview` → `wrangler versions upload --env preview` (a *version* of `{{ worker_name }}-preview`, bound to `{{ d1_database_name }}-preview`)

Two Workers, one repo. The trigger split is required because Workers Builds connections are per-Worker — see "Preview environment" below.

One-time prerequisite: install the [Cloudflare Workers & Pages GitHub App](https://github.com/apps/cloudflare-workers-and-pages) on the repo's owner. The task detects an unauthorized app and prints the install link.

**Why two triggers.** Workers Builds has no "production branch" flag or "all non-production branches" API toggle — the dashboard's "Builds for non-production branches" checkbox is implemented as a second trigger with `branch_includes: ["*"]` + `branch_excludes: ["main"]`. The API also rejects that shape on PATCH of an existing main-only trigger; you have to create both triggers up front via POST. `branch_includes: ["*"]` alone (without `branch_excludes`) is rejected with error 12002.

**Preview URLs.** `preview_urls: true` in `wrangler.jsonc` gives every version stable URLs:

- `https://<version-id>-{{ worker_name }}.<subdomain>.workers.dev`
- `https://<branch>-{{ worker_name }}.<subdomain>.workers.dev`

Workers Builds auto-comments both on the PR.

**Durable Objects fallback.** Cloudflare disables those preview URLs whenever the Worker has a DO binding (DO state is global per-Worker; there's no per-version partitioning). `.github/workflows/preview.yml` covers the gap: if it sees `durable_objects.bindings` in `wrangler.jsonc`, it deploys a per-PR Worker named `{{ worker_name }}-pr-<n>` and sticky-comments the URL on the PR. Each PR's Worker is its own DO namespace by construction, so PRs can't trample each other's state. The preview shares the production D1 (same `database_id`) and skips migrations — same forward-compat trade-off as the Workers Builds preview path. Without DOs the workflow no-ops so it doesn't clobber Workers Builds. `.github/workflows/preview-cleanup.yml` deletes the preview Worker on PR close. Required repo secrets: `CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN` (Workers Scripts: Edit + D1: Edit) **or** `CLOUDFLARE_API_KEY` + `CLOUDFLARE_EMAIL` (global key fallback), plus `CLOUDFLARE_ACCOUNT_ID`.

`mise init` already uploaded `BETTER_AUTH_SECRET` and applied remote migrations. `mise run secret:put` (idempotent) rotates the secret.

`mise deploy` auto-patches `vars.BETTER_AUTH_URL` in `wrangler.jsonc` from the `*.workers.dev` URL that wrangler prints on the first deploy, then redeploys once so the Worker's origin matches the URL better-auth uses for redirects and cookies. Override it manually beforehand if you're fronting with a custom domain.

`mise run dev` runs Vite's dev server (with HMR) on :5173 and `wrangler dev` (Worker) on :8787 in parallel. Browse to `http://localhost:5173` — Vite's `server.proxy` in `web/vite.config.ts` forwards `/api` (and any other top-level paths the Worker is mounted on per `wrangler.jsonc` `run_worker_first`) to wrangler so the SPA sees a single origin. SPA source edits hot-reload in-place; Worker `src/**` edits trigger wrangler reload. The trap kills the background vite when wrangler exits (Ctrl+C, crash). Note: `BETTER_AUTH_URL` in `.dev.vars` must be `http://localhost:5173` for cookies / CSRF to line up — `mise init` and `mise run worktree-init` seed that.

`mise run web:build` + `mise run deploy` produce a real production bundle of the SPA into `web/dist` (which the Worker's `assets` binding serves at deploy time). For deployed environments only — the dev server doesn't read `web/dist`.

## Preview environment

`wrangler.jsonc` declares an `env.preview` block that defines a separate preview Worker (`{{ worker_name }}-preview`) bound to its own `{{ d1_database_name }}-preview` D1 (and a preview `BETTER_AUTH_URL`). It is reached two ways:

1. **Push-to-deploy via Workers Builds** — `mise run builds:connect` wires the non-main trigger on `{{ worker_name }}-preview`, so PR-branch pushes upload versions of the preview Worker via `wrangler versions upload --env preview`. PR previews surface at `<version>-{{ worker_name }}-preview.<subdomain>.workers.dev` and are auto-commented by Workers Builds. PR-branch traffic binds to `{{ d1_database_name }}-preview`, never to prod D1.
2. **Manual workstation deploys** — `mise run deploy:preview` runs `wrangler deploy --env preview` for ad-hoc end-to-end testing without going through CI.

Workers Builds connections are per-Worker — every trigger configured on a Worker can only upload to that Worker, regardless of `--env` or `--name` flags. The split (`main` trigger on `{{ worker_name }}`, non-main trigger on `{{ worker_name }}-preview`) is what makes the `--env preview` upload actually take effect; configuring the non-main trigger on the prod Worker would silently inherit the top-level config and bind PR traffic to prod D1.

Per-PR isolation is **not** provided. Every non-main branch shares the same preview Worker and the same preview DB. The first preview deploy of any branch applies that branch's migrations to the shared DB; if a later branch's migrations conflict, drop the `d1_migrations` table on the preview DB and re-run `mise run migrate:remote-preview`. For full per-PR isolation you'd switch to a per-PR Worker pattern (separate `--name` per PR) and ephemeral D1 creation, which is a much larger lift and not what this template provisions.

Bootstrap, in order:

```bash
mise run d1:create-preview         # creates {{ d1_database_name }}-preview, patches database_id
mise run migrate:remote-preview    # applies migrations to the preview D1
mise run deploy:preview            # creates the {{ worker_name }}-preview Worker (or new version),
                                   # auto-patches env.preview.vars.BETTER_AUTH_URL on first deploy
mise run secret:put-preview        # uploads BETTER_AUTH_SECRET to the preview Worker (one-time)
```

`mise init` runs the first two automatically when wrangler is authenticated. The third and fourth are gated because the preview Worker has to exist before you can set secrets on it, and the auto-URL patch only succeeds after a real deploy. Re-running `mise run deploy:preview` after the URL is patched is safe (it short-circuits) and is normally only used for one-off ad-hoc deploys; routine preview deploys come from Workers Builds on push.

Caveats:

- **Non-inheritable bindings** (`d1_databases`, `kv_namespaces`, `r2_buckets`, `send_email`, `vars`) must be **fully redeclared** inside `env.preview`. If you add a binding to the top-level config, mirror it under `env.preview` (or accept that preview won't have it).
- **Custom-domain `routes` are prod-only.** Preview is reachable solely via the Workers Builds preview URL (`<version>-{{ worker_name }}-preview.<account>.workers.dev`).
- **OAuth callbacks need separate preview entries** — Better Auth and any third-party OAuth provider that rejects unknown redirect URIs need the preview workers.dev URL added to their allowed-origins lists.
- **Secrets are per-environment.** Set them with `wrangler secret put <NAME> --env preview` (or via `mise run secret:put-preview` for `BETTER_AUTH_SECRET`).

## Observability

**Workers Logs: 100% by default, no head sampling.** `wrangler.jsonc` only enables `observability` (no `head_sampling_rate`), so every request produces a trace event. Pricing: 20M logs/month included on Workers Paid, then $0.60/M. There's a built-in safety valve — *if you ever blow past the daily portion of the monthly quota, Cloudflare auto-applies a 1% head sample for the rest of that day*, so a runaway log spike costs visibility, not money. To opt into per-Worker sampling on purpose (e.g. once you're at 100M+ req/mo), add `"head_sampling_rate": 0.X` under `observability` in `wrangler.jsonc`. Local `wrangler dev` is naturally exempt either way — its logs go to stdout, not Workers Logs.

**D1 read replication (mode=auto), enabled by default.** `mise run d1:replicate` (auto-run by `mise init`) PUTs `read_replication.mode = "auto"` on the prod database via the D1 API. Replication is free; it doesn't show up in `wrangler.jsonc` because it's a database-level setting, not a binding setting. Code keeps using `env.DB` against the primary by default — to actually serve reads from a replica, opt in per query by switching to the [Sessions API](https://developers.cloudflare.com/d1/best-practices/read-replication/):

```ts
const session = env.DB.withSession("first-unconstrained");
const rows = await session.prepare("SELECT * FROM user").all();
// session.getBookmark() — pin subsequent reads to the same point in time
```

`mise run worktree-init` pulls prod data into the local D1 via `wrangler d1 export --remote`; replication is enabled regardless so app-side reads benefit immediately.

**Logpush → R2: opt-in via `mise run logpush:setup`.** `wrangler.jsonc` sets `logpush: true` so the Worker is logpush-eligible, but no R2 bucket or Logpush job is created automatically. Run `mise run logpush:setup` when one of these reasons applies:

- **Retention beyond 7 days.** Workers Logs holds 7 days. R2 is forever — incident postmortems / billing reconciliation older than a week need it.
- **Compliance / SIEM ingestion.** Audits typically require logs out of the vendor dashboard, in S3-compatible storage you control.
- **Off-vendor analytics.** Querying with DuckDB / BigQuery / Athena over the gzipped NDJSON in R2, instead of the dashboard query UI.
- **Disaster recovery.** Your data, your bucket; survives a CF account incident or a future migration off the platform.

The task creates `{{ project_slug }}-logs` R2 bucket, mints an S3-compatible R2 access key (cached in `.cf-logpush-r2-creds.json`, gitignored), and creates a Logpush job that ships `workers_trace_events` to `r2://{{ project_slug }}-logs/{DATE}/...`. *Empirically verified*: Logpush is downstream of `head_sampling_rate` — sampled-out requests don't produce trace events for either Workers Logs or Logpush. With no head sampling (the default), R2 sees the full firehose. Rotate the R2 access key by deleting the `logpush-r2-{{ worker_name }}` token in the dashboard and removing `.cf-logpush-r2-creds.json`; the next `mise run logpush:setup` mints a fresh one.

## Auth-specific gotchas

These are pinned by `test/auth.test.ts` — if you change auth wiring, run `mise run test`.

- Better Auth requires `env.BETTER_AUTH_SECRET` (a wrangler secret) and `env.BETTER_AUTH_URL`. The Env type is augmented in `src/env.d.ts` to include `BETTER_AUTH_SECRET` since it's not in `wrangler.jsonc`.
- `options.ts` sets `advanced.ipAddress.ipAddressHeaders: ["cf-connecting-ip"]` — without this better-auth logs rate-limiter warnings on Workers.
- `auth-client.ts` POSTs `body: "{}"` on sign-out because better-auth parses the body as JSON and crashes on an empty stream.
- The auth handler expects `basePath: "/api/auth"` matching the Hono route mount.
- Password reset only works because `emailAndPassword.sendResetPassword` is set in the `auth()` factory — Better Auth refuses `/request-password-reset` without it. It's wired in `src/lib/better-auth/index.ts` (env-scoped, for the EMAIL binding), not in static `options.ts`. See "Password reset (email)" above; pinned by `test/password-reset.test.ts`.
- Better Auth's CSRF check ("Invalid origin") rejects any request whose Origin doesn't match `BETTER_AUTH_URL` or an entry in `trustedOrigins`. `src/lib/better-auth/index.ts` builds that list with three layers: it always trusts `http://localhost:*` and `http://127.0.0.1:*` (any port — so `wrangler dev`, the Vite dev server on any auto-bumped port, and multiple front-ends against one Worker all work in dev without config; safe because a cross-site attacker can never forge a localhost Origin), it auto-derives `https://*.<sub>.workers.dev` whenever `BETTER_AUTH_URL` itself is on workers.dev (so Workers Builds preview URLs work zero-config), and it merges in any extras from the comma-separated `BETTER_AUTH_TRUSTED_ORIGINS` env var. That last var is where you add a non-localhost dev origin — a tunnel/reverse-proxy hostname (e.g. `https://*.your-tunnel.example`), a tailscale IP, or an `/etc/hosts` alias. Set that var in `wrangler.jsonc` `vars` for custom-domain prod (covering workers.dev preview URLs the auto-derive can't see), or in `.dev.vars` for local dev when you hit the Worker via a hostname that doesn't match `BETTER_AUTH_URL` (a `/etc/hosts` entry, reverse proxy, alternate port). Prefer adding the alternate origin to `BETTER_AUTH_TRUSTED_ORIGINS` over editing `BETTER_AUTH_URL` so cookies stay on the canonical origin.{% if cloudflare_account_subdomain %} The template seeds `BETTER_AUTH_TRUSTED_ORIGINS` with `https://*.{{ cloudflare_account_subdomain }}.workers.dev` in both prod and `env.preview` `vars` (from the `cloudflare_account_subdomain` copier answer), so preview URLs pass auth on the very first Workers Builds run before `mise run deploy:preview` has a chance to patch BETTER_AUTH_URL away from `localhost:8787`.{% endif %}
